vim-matrix-screensaver
======================

Matrix digital-rain screensaver for Neovim.

Originally by [Don Yang](https://uguu.org) ([upstream](https://github.com/uguu-org/vim-matrix-screensaver)).
This fork rewrites the animation engine in Lua for Neovim and fixes rendering issues
from the original Vimscript version.

Features
--------

- Full-screen Matrix effect with stable green-on-black colors
- Movie-style glyph set: halfwidth katakana, numerals, Latin letters, and symbols
- Smooth animation without horizontal jitter
- Hidden cursor and command line while running
- Press any key to exit and restore your session
- Optional speed tuning via command arguments
- Headless test suite and GitHub Actions CI

Requirements
------------

- Neovim 0.5+ (0.11+ recommended for best key-handling via `vim.on_key`)

Install
-------

Clone into your Neovim data directory:

    git clone https://github.com/alexesba/vim-matrix-screensaver.git \
      ~/.local/share/nvim/site/pack/plugins/start/vim-matrix-screensaver

Or add the repository root to `runtimepath`.

Usage
-----

1. Open Neovim
2. Run `:Matrix` to start the screensaver (movie glyph set by default)
3. Press any key to exit

Character sets:

    :Matrix              " movie glyphs (default)
    :Matrix movie        " halfwidth katakana, numerals, Latin, symbols
    :Matrix classic      " original printable ASCII rain

Optional arguments set the per-column delay range (defaults: `1` and `5`):

    :Matrix movie 1 3
    :Matrix classic 2 6

Lower values animate faster. Both delay arguments must be positive integers and
`maxdelay` must be greater than `mindelay`.

The movie charset uses single-width characters only so columns stay aligned in
the terminal. Glyphs are based on frame-by-frame analysis from the opening
digital rain in *The Matrix* (see [this Stack Exchange
thread](https://scifi.stackexchange.com/questions/137575/is-there-a-list-of-the-symbols-shown-in-the-matrixthe-symbols-rain-how-many)):

- Halfwidth katakana such as `ｱ`, `ｦ`, `ﾊ` (a curated subset from the film)
- Arabic digits `0–5`, `7–9` (digit `6` is absent in the movie rain)
- The letter `Z` (the only Roman letter in the opening sequence)
- Punctuation: `: . " = * + - < > ¦ | _`
- Kanji `日` when the terminal renders it at single width

In the film the glyphs are mirrored horizontally because the viewer is inside
the code looking out ([Simon Whiteley, production
designer](https://beforesandafters.com/secrets-of-the-matrix-code/)). Terminals
cannot mirror fonts, so the plugin uses the documented Unicode characters
directly.

Project layout
--------------

    plugin/matrix.lua          :Matrix command entry point
    lua/matrix/screensaver.lua Animation engine
    lua/matrix/charset.lua     Classic and movie glyph sets
    tests/matrix_spec.lua      Test suite
    scripts/run_tests.sh       Test runner

Tests
-----

    ./scripts/run_tests.sh

Requires Neovim on your `PATH`. The suite verifies that the plugin loads,
`:Matrix` is registered, the random number generator stays stable, and the
screensaver starts and stops cleanly in headless mode.

Known limitations
-----------------

- Requires a single-window layout when starting (same as the original plugin).
  Save modified buffers before running to avoid extra windows on exit.
- If the window is resized below 8 rows or 10 columns while running, the
  screensaver stops automatically.
- Resizing below that threshold during a session can still lose buffer state,
  as in the original — avoid making the window too small while it is active.

